# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: evelina-london-children-s-hospital
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] The **2006 European heat wave** was a period of exceptionally hot weather that arrived at the end of June 2006 in certain European countries.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] The United Kingdom, Ireland, France, Belgium, the Netherlands, Luxembourg, Italy, Poland, the Czech Republic, Hungary, Germany and western parts of Russia were most affected.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] In the Netherlands, Belgium, Germany, Ireland and the United Kingdom, July 2006 was the warmest month since official measurements began.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] Belgium experienced two heat waves in July 2006.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] Before 1990, a heat wave occurred about once every 8 years.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] Currently, the country averages one heat wave per year.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] On 19 July 2006, temperatures throughout the entire country rose to 36.2 °C (97.2 °F), causing it, at that moment, to be the hottest July day since 1947.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] The highest temperatures were recorded at the stations of Kleine Brogel and Genk, which measured 37.5 °C (99.5 °F) and 38.3 °C (100.9 °F), respectively.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] In some regions, more particularly Limburg, 36 consecutive days of temperatures above 25 °C (77 °F) have been measured in one continuous local heat wave instead of two separate periods of hot weather (according to the official Belgian rules for registering a heat wave).
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] In most other parts of the country, the second heat wave lasted for 17 days.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] July 2006 became the warmest month in Belgian history, with an all-time high mean temperature of 23.0 °C (73.4 °F).
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] This broke the UK's previous July record by 0.5 °C set in July 1911, although it fell 2.0 °C short of the 38.5 °C (101.3 °F) all-time record of the time set in August 2003.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] Whilst a disputed 42.0 °C (107.6 °F) was recorded at Wisley Airfield on 18 July, this figure has never been accepted and the figure of 36.5 °C (97.7 °F) from 19 July is the highest acceptable value.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] This figure is generally deemed to be erroneous and it has been suggested that the recorded temperature was in fact 32.0 °C (89.6 °F).
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] Another theory is that the 42.0 °C (107.6 °F) record on 18 July 2006 was recorded in the sunshine, not in standard 'shaded' areas.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] Similar temperatures were recorded in the sunshine during a brief heatwave at Wimbledon on 1 July 2015.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] The heatwave even warmed the normally cool and wet Scottish summer, with Glasgow having a July high of 22.7 °C (72.9 °F) and low of 13.7 °C (56.7 °F), which made it the warmest month on record.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] Because of the northerly location and marine nature, it was not a heat wave in a general sense, but rather unusually warm weather.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] Drought was an issue in many parts of the United Kingdom after a very dry winter.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] There was warning of drought occurring from the early months of 2006.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] Following the dry winter, with extreme temperatures occurring in the country and little rain, increasing strain was put on water supplies, and hose-pipe bans were issued in many counties.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] The Environment Agency claimed that the UK may have had the most severe drought in 100 years.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] Some power cuts occurred, after lightning strikes and some due to large amounts of electricity used by air conditioners.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] In Central London on 27 July 2006 a series of power cuts hit Piccadilly Circus, Regent Street, Turner Broadcasting UK and Oxford Circus causing the closure of shops and businesses, when pre-existing faults were worsened by heavy demand.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] The Met Office confirmed that July 2006 was the warmest July, as well as the warmest single month, overall, across the UK, and a number of regional records were also broken.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] The tarmac on some roads melted in England, requiring application of crushed rock dust.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] In Germany most of the July temperature average records were broken.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] In Mannheim/Ludwigshafen a July average of 26 °C (79 °F) was recorded, which means a temperature anomaly of 6 °C (11 °F), which is a new record for a monthly average in Germany (in the same cities high temperatures reached over 40 °C (104 °F)).
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] In Berlin an average temperature of 25 °C (77 °F) was recorded (7 °C (13 °F) above normal).
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] Such numbers were recorded all over Germany.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] The biggest problem was the precipitation, which mostly fell in intense thunderstorms.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] At least 20 people died in this heatwave.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] Denmark experienced the warmest July ever with an average temperature (day and night) of 19.8 °C (67.6 °F), breaking a record of 19.5 °C (67.1 °F) set in 1994.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] It was the second-warmest month ever, behind August 1997 at 20.4 °C (68.7 °F).
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] It was also the sunniest July ever, and the second-sunniest ever, at 321 hours.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] In fact, the previous July record was 290 hours.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] Since Denmark escaped the extremes seen further south, it is now known as one of the best summer months in history.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] On 25 June, the temperature reached 34.9 °C (94.8 °F) in Odense.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] High temperatures in France destroyed many crops, just days before the harvest period, while French officials said at least 40 people were confirmed to have been killed by the heat wave directly.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] Temperatures as high as 37 °C (99 °F) were recorded in Paris during the heatwave.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] July 2006 was in many regions the warmest July ever recorded (and often the second warmest month after August 2003).
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] In many regions weather was particularly stormy.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] In Nice, the all-time high temperature record was beaten with a 37.7 °C (99.9 °F) recorded on 1 August.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] Ireland was affected from the heat wave from the start of June, and the warm weather continued until the end of July.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] Temperatures were well above average for both months.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] The highest recorded in June was 27.1 °C (80.8 °F) at Ardfert, County Kerry on 9 June.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] In Kilkenny, County Kilkenny, there were 29 consecutive days in July with temperatures over 20.0 °C (68.0 °F), and nine of these days had temperatures over 25.0 °C (77.0 °F).
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] July 2006 was the warmest July in Ireland since records began.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] By the end of July, temperatures returned to average figures.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] On 18 July, a temperature of 30.1 °C (86.2 °F) was recorded in Birr, County Offaly; the same day, 30.2 °C (86.4 °F) was recorded at Kilkenny Castle, County Kilkenny and Shannon Airport, County Clare.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] However, temperatures again rose to 31.0 °C (87.8 °F) at Casement Aerodrome, Dublin; and 32.3 °C (90.1 °F) at Elphin, County Roscommon on the 19 July – this is the warmest temperature recorded in Ireland since 1976.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] Temperatures over 30.0 °C (86.0 °F) are rare in Ireland, being recorded about once or twice every decade – 1976, 1983, 1989, 1995, 2003 and now 2006 are the most recent times of such high temperatures.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] The highest ever recorded in Ireland was 33.3 °C (91.9 °F) at Kilkenny Castle, County Kilkenny on 26 June 1887.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] The highest mean temperatures during the heatwave were recorded at Merrion Square in Dublin city centre both months – 16.3 °C (61.3 °F) in June (average 14.6 °C (58.3 °F)) and 18.7 °C (65.7 °F) in July (average 16.3 °C (61.3 °F)).
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] To put this into context, average daily maxima in Ireland in only vary from 15 to 20 °C (59 to 68 °F) in June; and 16 to 23 °C (61 to 73 °F) in July.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] Despite the high daytime temperatures, night time temperatures were sometimes below average (6 to 11 °C (43 to 52 °F) in June; 8 to 13 °C (46 to 55 °F) in July).
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] Grass temperatures as low as −2.3 °C (27.9 °F) were recorded at Birr, County Offaly on 23 June; however, the lowest air temperature recorded was 2.0 °C (35.6 °F) at Straide, County Mayo on 14 June.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] The cool night time temperatures are thought to have made the heat wave more bearable there.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] The sunniest day during the two months (and indeed, the year) was on 25 June, when Malin Head, County Donegal, recorded 15.8 hours of sunshine.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] Rainfall levels were quite low, with only 13.2 millimetres (0.52 in) of rain at Derrygreenagh, County Offaly and Fermoy, County Cork in June and 13.0 millimetres (0.51 in) of rain recorded at Merrion Square, Dublin in July.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] Parts of Munster and Leinster also recorded 21 days between 28 May and 17 June where no rainfall was recorded.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] There was also a period between 9 July and 27 July when no rainfall was recorded in Greater Dublin.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] Despite the low rainfall, drought was not an issue in Ireland.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] In Ireland, May 2006 was the warmest for 20 years and sunniest since 2000.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] June 2006 was the sunniest on record, driest since 1995 and also one of the warmest.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] July 2006 was the warmest on record, sunniest in 15 years and also driest since 1989.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] September 2006 was the warmest on record.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] October 2006 was the warmest in many places since 2001 and sunniest since 2000.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] November 2006 was warmer and sunnier than usual.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] Overall, Summer 2006 (June, July and August) was the sunniest, driest and warmest summer since 1995 and one of the sunniest, driest and warmest on record.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] Autumn 2006 (September, October, November) was the warmest on record in many places, and sunshine levels were well above normal.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] Rainfall levels were also above average.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] The months of June and July 2006 are regarded as one of the best summers ever due to the high levels of sunshine, warm temperatures and low rainfall.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] Drought and health problems were not an issue in Ireland, unlike many parts of Europe – mostly because the heat was not as severe there.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] The Four Day Marches of Nijmegen were cancelled after only one day as hundreds of people collapsed the first day, two of them eventually dying due to fatal heat stroke.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] The walking people had to walk on open roads without any shade and there was not enough water for everyone.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] Paramedics had their hands full with hundreds of people who fainted due to the heat.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] The walking people had to deal with temperatures in the sun of 42 °C (108 °F).
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] The air-temperatures on the first day of the four-day march was about 36 °C (97 °F).
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] Forecasts showed even higher temperatures of 37 °C (99 °F) for the next day, causing the organisation to cancel the remainder of the event.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] The highest temperature was recorded on 19 July, when temperatures reached the mid- to upper 30s °C (mid- to upper 90s °F) for most of the country, especially in the south-east.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] The all-time record for the month of July was broken.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] A few hundred meters across the border into Germany, at the weather station Kalkar, located at the airport in Weeze, near Nijmegen, a maximum of 38.6 °C (101.5 °F) was recorded on 19 July.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] At some places especially in the south-east of the Netherlands temperatures passed 30 °C (86 °F) for 15 or 16 days.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] The average daytime temperature for the month was 30 °C (86 °F) again in the south-east of the Netherlands.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] The lowest daytime temperature was at some locations 34.1 °C (93.4 °F) for the whole month of July.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] For two days the daytime temperatures were below 25 °C (77 °F), making 29 days with temperatures of 25 °C (77 °F) and higher.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] During days when temperatures reached 30 °C (86 °F) or higher, and on days without wind, the smog level was very high.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] Warnings were broadcast on television and radio, advising people to stay indoors as much as possible because the air pollution was very unhealthy, the smog was very strong and it was dangerously hot.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] The Netherlands also had to deal with extreme drought in June and July.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] The rainfall in June was at some locations as low as 0.5 centimetres (0.20 in), July was also extremely dry.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] Because of the extreme heat and drought vegetation was very dry, and the humidity levels were very low, causing brushfires.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] On 30 January 2007, the United Nations published a report of all countries in the world with the most deaths related to natural disasters for 2006.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] The Netherlands appeared fourth place, with 1,000 heat-related deaths.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] On 19 July, the temperature reached 37.1°C in Westdorpe.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] July 2006 was the warmest in Poland since the beginning of the meteorological measurements (i.e.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] For most of the month, the maximum temperature exceeded 30 °C (86 °F) – even at night it rarely fell below 20 °C (68 °F).
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] The average temperature was more than 5 °C (9.0 °F) higher than normal, for example in Warsaw the average temperature in July 2006 is usually 23.5 °C (74.3 °F), in Wrocław 23.8 °C (74.8 °F), and in Poznań 24.2 °C (75.6 °F).
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] The highest temperature was recorded in Słubice, near the German border 36.5 °C (97.7 °F).
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] After the hot days, the temperature at night dropped very slowly.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] On 16 July in Słubice the temperature at night was 27.4 °C (81.3 °F) and it was the warmest night in the entire history of meteorological measurements.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] In many regions it did not rain for 3–4 weeks.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] The river water levels were the lowest ever reported in Polish history and in the absence of rain, many crops dried up.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] July 2006 in most Polish cities saw 300–350 sunshine hours (normally 220–240 sunshine hours): the highest number being in Poznań (373 sunshine hours) and in Warsaw (355 sunshine hours).
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] July 2007 was AGAIN normal month in Poland.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] Temperature rarely exceed 30 °C (86 °F) and it was warm, wet and wild.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] In many regions, including Elbląg rained and it was stormy.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] Many crops returned to normal business, temperature rarely at night exceed 20 °C (68 °F) and it was Cloudy, and sunny.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] According to the Swedish Meteorological and Hydrological Institute (SMHI), the city of Lund in Skåne in southern Sweden had the highest average temperatures (day and night: 21.7 °C (71.1 °F)) for the month of July since records began in 1859.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] The rest of Sweden has however not broken the daily average temperatures from the record year 1994.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] The highest temperature in Sweden in July 2006 was recorded in Målilla in Småland, where a temperature of 34.2 °C (93.6 °F) was recorded on 6 July.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] This is the highest temperature recorded in the country since July 1994 when Kalmar and Söderhamn had 35.1 °C (95.2 °F).
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] Målilla and Ultuna are the places where the highest temperature ever in Sweden was recorded, 38 °C (100 °F), in 1947 and 1933 respectively.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] Målilla was the warmest location during daytime, averaging 28.3 °C (82.9 °F), but with average lows being normal at 11.1 °C (52.0 °F) fell a whole degree short of Lund's aforementioned value, where the average high was 27.8 °C (82.0 °F) and low 15.6 °C (60.1 °F).
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] The summer was warmer than usual in all of Sweden, but north of Stockholm and the Mälar valley the temperatures fell quickly, with the exception of the usual hotspot of Falun where the average high was 26.3 °C (79.3 °F) in spite of its location a bit north of 60 degrees latitude.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] One day in August Stavropol reached +39.7 °C (103.5 °F).
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] Due to the extreme heat in July 2006, the ocean water reached a temperature normally reached in September.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] This increase in water temperature led to faster evaporation of ocean waters, making August one of the cloudiest and wettest months in recorded history in various western European countries.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] Many weather experts report this to be a direct consequence of the heat wave, as the high evaporation rate caused the atmosphere to generate many low pressure areas.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] Despite this, September 2006 was again the warmest September on record, in the UK and elsewhere, due to high ocean temperatures, altered atmospheric pressure zones, and consequent different wind directions over Europe.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] The pressure zone changes were a consequence of the extra-tropical remnants of Atlantic hurricanes settling over the British Isles.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] The Met Office announced on 16 October 2006 that the extended summer of May to September 2006 was the hottest summer ever recorded, the Central England temperature mean temperature of 16.2 °C (61.2 °F) for this summer was 2 °C (3.6 °F) warmer than the average temperatures of 1961–1990.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] Just two months after July 2006, September 2006 became the warmest September since official measurements started.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] Additionally, October 2006 and November 2006 broke several temperature records.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] October was one of the warmest Octobers since measurements began, and November went into the record books as the second warmest November since official measurements started three hundred years prior.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] With temperatures from the north of the Netherlands to the south of Belgium ranging between 16 and 18 °C (61 and 64 °F) at the end of November, previous records were shattered.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] The autumn of 2006 was the warmest autumn in history, breaking the old record of just one year prior (2005) by 1.4 °C (34.5 °F).
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] The winter of 2006/2007 was the warmest in three hundred years as well, and so was the following spring.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] Temperatures reached a record-breaking 29.7 °C (85.5 °F) as early as 15 April.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] The average April daytime maximum in the Netherlands is around 12 °C (54 °F).
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] Such a sequence of events is unheard of in the Netherlands meteorological history, estimated to happen every 8,000 years when not taking global warming into account.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] After the record-breaking month of July, August broke records on the opposite end.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] Some places registered more than 200 millimetres (7.9 in) of rain and received a total sunshine amount of only 90 hours, which is less than half the expected sunshine for a typical August month and a record low for any summer month in Uccle.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] The average temperature was about 16.3 °C (61.3 °F).
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] September 2006 has been the warmest autumn month in Belgian history, with an average temperature of 18.4 °C (65.1 °F), while the normal temperature is 14.6 °C (58.3 °F) (1971-2000 normals), exceptionally preceding a much colder August month.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] October 2006 has been the second warmest in history with an average temperature of 14.2 °C (57.6 °F) (normal average for 1971-2000: 10.5 °C (50.9 °F)).
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] November 2006 has been the 4th warmest month in history, with an average temperature of 9.1 °C (48.4 °F) (normal average for 1971-2000: 6.1 °C (43.0 °F)).
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] The autumn of 2006, at that moment, had been the warmest autumn season in recorded history with an average temperature of 13.9 °C (57.0 °F), which was 3 °C above the normal average for the climatological period 1971-2000.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] As of 2021, this record still stands firmly.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] January 2007 broke every temperature record (minimum, maximum and average).
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] The average temperature was 7.2 °C (45.0 °F), while the normal was just 2.6 °C (36.7 °F).
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] February 2007 set some daily records and was 2 °C warmer than normal.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] The winter of 2007, just like the previous autumn season, has also been the warmest in recorded history.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] March 2007 was the 6th warmest month in history, just 0.8 °C less than the record at that time.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] April 2007 broke the all-time temperature records once again, as the average temperature had been 5 °C warmer than normal.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] Kleine Brogel had two tropical days on 15 and 16 April 2007 (30 °C (86 °F) and 30.7 °C (87.3 °F)), which have been the earliest dates any place in Belgium had ever seen temperatures at or over 30°C.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] May started warmer than normal, but a 9-month warmth streak eventually came to an end when June returned to average temperatures around normal.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] The summer of 2006 was around 2 °C warmer than the 1971–2000 average.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] While the heat was not record breaking, the drought was: less than half of the average summer rainfall was received in large areas, and almost all of the country received less than 75% of the usual rain.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] In many localities (such as Jokioinen, Kajaani and Rovaniemi, it was the driest summer on record.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] Autumn 2006 was also 1 to 2 °C (34 to 36 °F) warmer than the average.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] While this didn't break any records, an unprecedented period of mild weather began around the middle of November.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] December 2006 was the warmest December ever recorded in Finland.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] In Helsinki, the December mean temperature was 4 °C (39 °F), beating the previous record of 2.9 °C (37.2 °F) set in 1929.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] Similar records were broken across the southern and central parts of the country, while in the north the old records narrowly remained in place.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] On 6 December, an all time December high of 10.8 °C (51.4 °F) was recorded at Salo.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] The mild weather continued well into January 2007.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] On January 10, many places in southern Finland observed record highs for January.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] (The national record high for January, 10.9 °C (51.6 °F) set at Mariehamn in 1973, remained in place.) As a whole, the two months leading to 16 January were the mildest such period ever recorded in Finland.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] In Helsinki, the mean temperature for this period was 4.1 °C (39.4 °F), beating the previous record of 2.2 °C (36.0 °F) set in 1982–83.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] In the second half of January, temperatures plunged and February 2007 was well below the average over 1971 to 2000.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] After the unusually hot July, August brought a big contrast with cool weather, cloudy skies and pretty wet weather patterns all around the country, with the exception of the Mediterranean coast.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] September however turned to be very warm and sunny and in many parts of France it was the warmest in 50 years.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] October too was very warm and so was November, triggering in many regions the warmest autumn in recorded history.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] A very rare föhn-like warm spell affected northern and western France on 25 November and brought temperature as high as 18 °C (64 °F) at 7 in the morning in Paris.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] December, January and February also brought extremely mild weather making the winter of 2006/2007 the warmest in recorded history.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] March was relatively uneventful with average temperatures and precipitations.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] However April broke the record for the warmest April on record.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] In many regions it was also the sunniest (with almost uninterrupted sunshine for the whole 30 days) and the driest April on record.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] In northern and north-eastern France the departure from the normal of the average temperature was as high as 5 °C (9 °F).
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] May was too very warm making the spring 2007 the warmest in recorded history for some regions.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] Like the rest of Western Europe, August 2006 saw a dramatic turnaround, being a cloudy and wet month in many parts with daytime maxima below average – although the Central England Temperature (CET) was close to the long-term average, due to the cloud keeping night minima higher than normal.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] The month was notable for its lack of heat waves, being the first August since 1993 when 30 °C (86 °F)) was not recorded anywhere in the country.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] Met Office: UK climate: August 2006 However, August 2008, which followed a much cooler July, was even duller and wetter.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] August 2010 again followed a similar pattern.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] September 2006 was just as record-breaking as July, being the warmest on record and just as exceptionally, warmer than August had been.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] October and November, although not beating the records for the warmest set in 2001 and 1994 respectively, were also much warmer than average.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] Winter 2006/07 was exceptionally mild, the warmest since 1868/69.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] April 2007 was another record-breaker, with a CET of 11.2 °C (52.2 °F) the warmest in over 300 years of temperature records and by a large margin (10.6c being previous record).
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] This record was broken 4 years later in 2011 with a CET of 11.8 °C (53.2 °F).
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] Temperatures were widely above 20 °C (68 °F), with over 200 hours of sunshine for much of the country.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] Parts of south-eastern Britain had no rain all month.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] After a hot and dry July, August 2006 was cold and very rainy.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] The average temperature hovered slightly below the long-term standards.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] At the beginning of the month in the west of the country experienced torrential rains and violent storms.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] In Wrocław decreased 292 millimetres (11.5 in) of water; that is 4 times more than usual.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] As a result of heavy rains came the floods, which affected mainly Lower Silesia.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] For a change September 2006 was warm and dry.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] In the west, that month was more than 4 °C (7.2 °F) warmer than the norm.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] In Słubice the average temperature was until 18.0 °C (64.4 °F).
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] Early September brought gusty winds in Poland, near Bydgoszcz in Kuyavian-Pomeranian Voivodeship tornado passed, which escaped with the roots of several hundred trees.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] October 2006 is also inscribed as one of the warmer in the history of meteorological measurements, as well as very dry.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] For many days the temperature exceeded 20 °C (68 °F) degrees, reaching up to 26 °C (79 °F) at the south of the country.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] It was also very sunny month, because reported about 150 sunshine hours.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] November 2006 in Poland was the warmest from 10 years.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] The daily temperature reached up to 20 °C (68 °F) and at night rarely dropped below 0 °C (32 °F).
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] November was very wet, usually dropped 100 millimetres (3.9 in) of water, and the standard is approximately 40 millimetres (1.6 in).
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] Like in October the wind was blowing strongly, particularly on the coast of the Baltic Sea.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] At the end of the month, thick fog blocked airports in Warsaw, Kraków and Wrocław to 3 days.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] Winter 2006/2007 was extremely warm and rainy, in many cities, the snow lay only a few days, and rain fell for MANY days.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] At night the temperature increased up to 14 °C (57 °F) degrees, which at this time of year, it was an unprecedented phenomenon.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] In January 2007, the maximum temperature increased to 20 °C (68 °F), especially in the south, where often blow halny – a foehn wind, and in Elbląg during the day 13 °C (55 °F), and at night 10 °C (50 °F).
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] This conclusion was the warmest winter since the measurements.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] In March 2007, in Elbląg this month was snow-less, but it rained and the temperature reached up to 17 °C (63 °F), and at night of 22nd of March 8 °C (46 °F).
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] It rained a lot, temperatures reached down to −1 °C (30 °F) in the Polish-Czech/Tatra hills, temps reached up to 35 °C (95 °F), but it lasted for only 2-3 days, and temperature fell down.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] December 2006 and January 2007 were the warmest months in Moscow, Saint Petersburg, Kazan and other cities of European Russia.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/2006-european-heat-wave] 2007 and 2008 became the warmest years in Moscow history with average year temperatures +7.1 °C (44.8 °F) (2nd) and +7.3 °C (45.1 °F) (1st).
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/academic-dress-of-king-s-college-london] Prior to 2008, the Academic dress of King's was similar to that of the University of London's which, like most academic dress, is based on medieval attire.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/academic-dress-of-king-s-college-london] Graduates of the University of London have been formally presented to the Chancellor of the university since 1849, and the first public presentation of the university was held at King's Great Hall in 1850.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/academic-dress-of-king-s-college-london] From 1903 to 1992 this university ceremony was continued in the Royal Albert Hall, and King's first held its own ceremony in 1989.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/academic-dress-of-king-s-college-london] In 1995, the University of London granted some of its constituent colleges the power to confer degrees on behalf of the university.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/academic-dress-of-king-s-college-london] In 2007, in line with the evolution of the university's constituent colleges, King's successfully petitioned the Privy Council for its degree-awarding powers in its own right; these powers were first used in 2008.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/academic-dress-of-king-s-college-london] Such development in securing its own degree-awarding powers brought the need for King's to design its own academic dress.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/academic-dress-of-king-s-college-london] During the transition phase, global fashion icon Dame Vivienne Westwood was approached by Patricia Rawlings, Baroness Rawlings, then Chairperson of King's College London, to design an academic gown of the institution.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/academic-dress-of-king-s-college-london] Working with Ede & Ravenscroft, the producers of the academic dress, the Westwood-designed academic dresses for King's College London have been unveiled in 2008.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/academic-dress-of-king-s-college-london] On the gowns, Vivienne Westwood commented: "Through my reworking of the traditional robe I tried to link the past, the present and the future.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/academic-dress-of-king-s-college-london] The 'new' academic gowns were showcased at the first graduation of summer 2008, where Westwood and former Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, Lord Smith of Finsbury were among those wearing the gowns as they received their King's College London Honorary Fellowships.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/academic-dress-of-king-s-college-london] Westwood-designed academic dress features two long (4') stole-like streamers which serve as gown facings.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/academic-dress-of-king-s-college-london] Westwood's unique but unifying style for King's academic dress is the King's College London lion gold button on each shoulder.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/academic-dress-of-king-s-college-london] Influenced by University of London's tradition, being the first university in the world to devise a system of academic dress based on faculty colours, the gowns and hoods have been designed with colours that reflect the university's faculties/schools/institutes of study and the level of the degree.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/academic-dress-of-king-s-college-london] Owing to its unique shape, the hood cannot be folded flat.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/academic-dress-of-king-s-college-london] The hood may be made with a neckband but this is strictly for use by clergy who require to wear the hood over a surplice and are not to be used for university ceremonies.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/academic-dress-of-king-s-college-london] The scheme does not provide for a hat, though mortarboards may be hired for the day or provided for photography (they are not allowed to be worn during graduation ceremonies).
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/academic-dress-of-king-s-college-london] The King's gowns and hoods have been designed with colours to reflect the academic faculties or schools.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/academic-dress-of-king-s-college-london] All hoods and gowns for first degrees are black, lined with a certain colour.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/academic-dress-of-king-s-college-london] Graduates are distinguished by the colour lining of the hood and stole, which denotes the respective Faculty, School or Institute.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/academic-dress-of-king-s-college-london] Postgraduate master's level graduates wear black gowns with hood, lined with a certain colour.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/academic-dress-of-king-s-college-london] A colour lining is also present on the sleeves.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/academic-dress-of-king-s-college-london] As with first degree recipients, the Faculty/School/Institute is denoted by the colour.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/academic-dress-of-king-s-college-london] For Master of Philosophy (MPhil), graduates wear a black gown, and a black hood attached to the gown on each shoulder with a King's lion button; the sleeve vents, cape and cowl are bound in blue with the binding extending over the shoulders.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/academic-dress-of-king-s-college-london] For research degree [i.e., PhD/MD (Res)] graduates wear a dark red gown, and a dark red hood attached to the gown on each shoulder with a King's lion button; the sleeve vents, cape and cowl are bound in blue with the binding extending over the shoulders.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/academic-dress-of-king-s-college-london] Using the Groves classification system, such research graduates wear a King's Full [f12] shape gown of deep red cloth, with stole of purple silk.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/academic-dress-of-king-s-college-london] The sleeves are held back by purple linings and gold buttons.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/academic-dress-of-king-s-college-london] The hood is fully lined with purple silk.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/academic-dress-of-king-s-college-london] Specialist doctors (EdD/DClinPsy/DHC/DrPS/DthMin) graduates wear a blue gown, and a blue hood attached to the gown on each shoulder with a King's lion button.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/academic-dress-of-king-s-college-london] The sleeve vents, cape and cowl are bound in dark red with the binding extending over the shoulders; a King's Full [f12] shape gown of deep blue cloth, with stole of red silk.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/academic-dress-of-king-s-college-london] Students graduating who have also completed the tradition of Associateship of King's College (AKC), will wear as part of their academic gown a black *epitoge* with a golden embroidery of the university's lion 'Reggie', buttoned to the left shoulder.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/academic-dress-of-king-s-college-london] The epitoge is a short streamer of black fabric which matches the fabric of King's gowns.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/academic-dress-of-king-s-college-london] PG certificate and diploma recipients wear black gowns with King's Simple hood [s12].
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/academic-dress-of-king-s-college-london] The various officers of King's wear their official robes, while members of the academe wear the academic dress of the university from which they graduated; such would include that of other universities in the UK as well as around the world.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The site was previously occupied by a mansion known as Alder Hey which the local poor law guardians acquired for use as a children's home in 1910.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The mansion was converted for use as a military hospital in 1914.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] During the First World War, the United States Army established Camp Hospital 40 on the site, operated by Hospital Unit Q and, subsequently, Unit W.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] American sources commonly refer to Alder Hey as being within Liverpool's Knotty Ash area.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] During the Second World War, parts of the hospital were again used to treat injured military personnel.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The Liverpool Neonatal Surgical Unit opened at the hospital in 1953.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] This unit was the first neonatal intensive care unit in the United Kingdom.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The opening was largely due to the efforts of Isabella Forshall, a paediatric surgeon.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In 1990 when Myrtle Street Children's Hospital (founded in 1869 and previously known as Royal Liverpool Children's Hospital) closed, Alder Hey absorbed its A&E department.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The hospital authority was one of 57 such bodies which became an NHS hospital trust in 1991.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Ronald McDonald House, a home for the families of sick children, opened in 1993.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In 1999 an inquiry was instituted into the Alder Hey organs scandal and to investigate the hospital's practices in respect of removal and retention of human tissue.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The inquiry had far-reaching effects throughout the UK hospital system and provided the impetus for the Human Tissue Act 2004.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In August 2008 the Royal Liverpool Children's NHS Trust became an NHS foundation trust and changed its name to Alder Hey NHS Foundation Trust.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Between 2010 and 2014 the number of doctors employed at the trust increased from 269 to 344, while the number of managers increased from 70 to 86.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] At the end of March 2017, the trust was confirmed as one of four additional NHS Global Digital Exemplars, joining the twelve announced in September 2016.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey had its centenary year in 2014, the last year in which it operated from the buildings on its original site.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] A new hospital was procured under Private Finance Initiative contract in neighbouring Springfield Park.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The works, which were carried out by Laing O'Rourke at a cost of £187 million, began on 26 March 2013 and the hospital opened in October 2015.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] It was Europe's first children's hospital built in a park.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The original Alder Hey buildings were mostly demolished and the land was reclaimed as new parkland for the surrounding community.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Features of the new hospital include access to play areas, natural light and striking views of the park are available wherever possible Children and young people were involved with the design of the new hospital.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] A drawing of a flower by teenage patient Eleanor Brogan impressed architects and inspired their final design.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The hospital is a centre of excellence for oncology and muscular dystrophy as well as spinal, heart and brain conditions.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey has Europe's first 3T Intraoperative MRI scanner which is a pioneering technology for neurosurgery, providing surgeons with extremely high resolution images and reducing the need for repeat operations in 90% of cases.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] It currently employs about 2,400 staff and treats over 270,000 children from across the UK each year.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey conducts paediatric research into children's medicines, infection, inflammation and oncology.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] It has research partners including the University of Liverpool and is a member of Liverpool Health Partners.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey conducts more than 100 clinical research studies on an ongoing basis, ranging from observation to clinical trials.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The hospital is within the National Institute for Health and Care Research's Top 100 Performing Trust's for participation recruitment in 2013/14.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey was a finalist in the Clinical Research Impact category of the 2013 HSJ Awards and in 2014 the innovation team received the Health Service Journal Award for improving health care with technology.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In 2016 the first phase of a bespoke research, education and innovation centre, Institute in the Park, opened next to Alder Hey in the Park.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In November 2015, the institute hosted a children's health Hackathon in conjunction with Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey Children's Charity supports the work of the hospital.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In addition to NHS funding which covers the running costs of the hospital, Alder Hey relies on charitable support.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Funds are spent directly on initiatives in the hospital to benefit patients.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] It funds research initiatives, patient and family enhancements and state of the art medical equipment.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Known as the 'Imagine Appeal' until 2012, Alder Hey Children's Charity is based within the hospital.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] On 14 October 2013 the charity launched a public appeal to raise £30m to fund equipment, facilities and research at Alder Hey's new hospital, Alder Hey in the Park.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In October 2015 the charity announced over £20m had been raised.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In 2009 charitable support allowed Alder Hey to buy Europe's first 3T intraoperative MRI scanner.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In one charitably funded project, the sound recordist and musician Chris Watson was employed to devise an art project, using bird song recordings made by children to calm other young patients as they received injections and other treatments.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In 1978, the charity Art For Their Sake, a team of volunteer artists led by founder George Nicholas (now of Ormskirk, England), produced the world's longest mural in the corridors of Alder Hey Children's Hospital.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] A Guinness Record was set with a total of 17,963 square feet of murals, and awarded to the hospital in 1986.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Nicholas and his team continued to work on these murals for a period of 30 years, adding to as well as restoring and maintaining, for a total of over 34,000 square feet.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey runs an Arts for Health programme, funded entirely through charitable sources including Alder Hey Children's Charity.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The programme aims to enhance the experience of being a patient and includes animation projects, music and dance therapy, creative writing, comedy workshops and storytelling.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] An international child health development programme led by Alder Hey clinicians focuses on humanitarian work in developing countries.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The programme includes provision of immediate medical support, knowledge sharing and involvement with international clinical trials.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The programme has undertaken work across Africa and Asia, including Pakistan, Malawi, Nepal and India.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] During the 1990s, Alder Hey was featured in the BBC television series *Children's Hospital*.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In 2011, chef Heston Blumenthal took to the challenge of changing the dinner menu of Alder Hey Children's Hospital on his televised show, *Heston's Mission Impossible*.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Since September 2012, Alder Hey has regularly featured on the CBBC television series *Operation Ouch!*.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In October 2013, the Care Quality Commission's Intelligent Monitoring system placed Alder Hey in category one, meaning it would be amongst the first hospitals to be inspected under a new style of inspection.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In May 2014, Alder Hey was inspected by the Care Quality Commission and was given the overall rating Requires Improvement.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In June 2015, Alder Hey was re-inspected by the Care Quality Commission and was given the overall rating Good, and was rated Outstanding in the Caring category.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Another inspection took place in 2018, the overall rating was unchanged.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Dame Josephine Williams was appointed Chair of the Trust Board in February 2019.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Louise Shepherd CBE was appointed Chief Executive of the trust in March 2008.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] On 26 January 2023, the Alder Hey Children's Hospital NHS Foundation Trust was granted the Honorary Freedom of the Metropolitan Borough of Sefton.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] Served mostly by a shuttle train and having low passenger numbers, the station and branch were considered for closure several times.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] Service was offered only during weekday peak hours from 1962 and discontinued in 1994, when the cost of replacing the lifts was considered too high for the income generated.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] Disused parts of the station and the running tunnels were used during both world wars to shelter artworks from London's public galleries and museums from bombing.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] The station is the work of Leslie Green and has long been popular as a filming location, appearing as itself and as other London Underground stations in a number of films.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] In recognition of its historical significance, the station is a Grade II listed building and is an example of the Modern Style (British Art Nouveau style).
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] London Transport Museum runs guided tours of the station via its "Hidden London" programme throughout the year.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] The tour takes visitors through the ticket hall, the original lifts, disused platforms and tunnels; and shares findings from the museum's archives on the history of the site.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] The Great Northern and Strand Railway (GN&SR) first proposed a station in the parish of St Clement Danes in a private bill presented to Parliament in November 1898.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] The station was to be the southern terminus of an underground railway line planned to run from Wood Green station (now Alexandra Palace) via Finsbury Park and King's Cross and was originally to be located at the corner of Stanhope Street and Holles Street, north of the Strand.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] When the two streets were scheduled for demolition as part of the London County Council's plans for the construction of Kingsway and Aldwych, the GN&SR moved the location to the junction of the two new roads.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] Royal assent to the bill was given and the Great Northern and Strand Railway Act 1899 was enacted on 1 August.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] In September 1901, the GN&SR was taken over by the Brompton and Piccadilly Circus Railway (B&PCR), which planned to build an underground line from South Kensington to Piccadilly Circus via Knightsbridge.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] Both were under the control of Charles Yerkes through his Metropolitan District Electric Traction Company and, in June 1902, were transferred to Yerkes' new holding company, the Underground Electric Railways Company of London (UERL).
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] Neither of the railways had carried out any construction, but the UERL obtained permission for new tunnels between Piccadilly Circus and Holborn to connect the two routes.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] The companies were formally merged as the Great Northern, Piccadilly and Brompton Railway (GNP&BR) following approval in the Great Northern and Strand Railway Act 1902 (2 Edw.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] Prior to confirmation of the merger, the GN&SR had sought permission to extend its line southwards from the future junction of Kingsway and Aldwych, under Norfolk Street to a new interchange under the Metropolitan District Railway's station at Temple.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] The extension was rejected following objections from the Duke of Norfolk under whose land the last part of the proposed tunnels would have run.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] In 1903, the GNP&BR sought permission for a branch from Piccadilly Circus to run under Leicester Square, Strand, and Fleet Street and into the City of London.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] The branch would have passed and interchanged with the already approved Strand station, allowing travel on the GNP&BR from Strand in three directions.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] The deliberations of the Royal Commission on London Traffic prevented parliamentary consideration of the proposal, which was withdrawn.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] In 1905, with the royal commission's report about to be published, the GNP&BR returned to Parliament with two bills for consideration.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] The first bill revived the 1903 proposal for a branch from Piccadilly Circus to the City of London, passing and interchanging with Strand station.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] The second proposed an extension and relocation of Strand station to the junction of Strand and Surrey Street.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] From there the line was to continue as a single tunnel under the River Thames to Waterloo.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] The first bill was again delayed and withdrawn.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] Of the second, it became the Great Northern, Piccadilly and Brompton Railway (Various Powers) Act 1905 (5 Edw.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] 7. c. clxiii), but only the relocation of Strand station was permitted.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] The linking of the GN&SR and B&PCR routes meant that the section of the GN&SR south of Holborn became a branch from the main route.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] The UERL began constructing the main route in July 1902.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] Progress was rapid, so that it was largely complete by the Autumn of 1906.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] Construction of the Holborn to Strand section was delayed while the London County Council constructed Kingsway and the tramway subway running beneath it and while the UERL decided how the junction between the main route and the branch would be arranged at Holborn.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] Strand station was built on the site of the Royal Strand Theatre, which had closed on 13 May 1905 and been demolished.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] Construction of the station began on 21 October 1905, to a design by the UERL's architect Leslie Green in the UERL house style of a two-storey steel-framed building faced with red glazed terracotta blocks, with wide semi-circular windows on the upper floor.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] The station building is L-shaped, with two façades separated by the building on the corner of Strand and Surrey Street.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] The Strand façade is narrow with a single semi-circular window above the entrance.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] The façade in Surrey Street is wider with a separate entrance and exit and a shop unit.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] In anticipation of a revival of the extension to Waterloo and the City route, the station was built with three circular lift shafts able to accommodate six trapezium-shaped lifts.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] Only one of the shafts was fitted out, with two lifts.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] The other two shafts rose from the lower concourse to the basement of the station, but could have been extended upwards into the space of the shop unit when required.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] A fourth smaller-diameter shaft accommodated an emergency spiral stair.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] The platforms are 92 feet 6 inches (28.2 m) below street level and are 250 feet (76 m) long; shorter than the GNP&BR's standard length of 350 feet (110 m).
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] As with other UERL stations, the platform walls were tiled with distinctive patterns, in this case cream and dark green.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] Only parts of the platform walls were decorated because it was planned to operate the branch with short trains.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] Owing to the reduced lift provision, a second route between the platforms and lifts was never brought into use and was left in an unfinished condition without tiling.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] The GNP&BR's main route opened on 15 December 1906, but the Strand branch was not opened until 30 November 1907.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] Initially, shuttle trains operated to Holborn from the eastern platform into the through platform at Holborn.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] At peak times, an additional train operated alternately in the branch's western tunnel into the bay platform at Holborn.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] During the first year of operation, a train for theatregoers operated late on Monday to Saturday evenings from Strand through Holborn and northbound to Finsbury Park; this was discontinued in October 1908.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] In March 1908, the off-peak shuttle service began to use the western platform at Strand and the through platform at Holborn, crossing between the two branch tunnels south of Holborn.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] Low usage led to the withdrawal of the second peak-hour shuttle and the eastern tunnel was taken out of use in 1914.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] On 9 May 1915, three of the Underground stations in the area were renamed and Strand station became Aldwych.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] Sunday services ended in April 1917 and, in August of the same year, the eastern tunnel and platform at Aldwych and the bay platform at Holborn were formally closed.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] A German bombing campaign in September 1917 led to the disused platform being used as storage for around 300 paintings from the National Gallery from then until December 1918.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] In October 1922, the ticket office was replaced by a facility in the lifts.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] Passenger numbers remained low: when the station was one of a number on the network considered for closure in 1929, its annual usage was 1,069,650 and takings were £4,500.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] The branch was again considered for closure in 1933, but remained open.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] Wartime efficiency measures led to the branch being closed temporarily on 22 September 1940, shortly after the start of The Blitz, and it was partly fitted out by the City of Westminster as an air-raid shelter.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] The tunnels between Aldwych and Holborn were used to store items from the British Museum, including the Elgin Marbles.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] The branch reopened on 1 July 1946, but patronage did not increase.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] In 1958, the station was one of three that London Transport announced would be closed.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] Again it survived, but the service was reduced in June 1958 to run during Monday to Friday peak hours and Saturday morning and early afternoons.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] The Saturday service was withdrawn in June 1962.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] After operating only during peak hours for more than 30 years, the closure announcement came on 4 January 1993.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] The original 1907 lifts required replacement at a cost of £3 million.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] This was not considered justifiable in relation to the passenger numbers using the station and it was losing London Regional Transport £150,000 per year.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] The Secretary of State for Transport granted permission on 1 September 1994 to close the station, and the branch closed on 30 September.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] Recognising the station's historical significance as a mostly unaltered station from the early 20th century, the station was given Grade II listed building status in 2011.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] Office floors above the station are used by the Classics department of King's College London, and part of the station is used by the university's Rifle and Pistol Club.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] Although the Piccadilly Circus to City of London branch proposal of 1905 was never revisited after its withdrawal, the early plan to extend the branch south to Waterloo was revived a number of times during the station's life.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] The extension was considered in 1919 and 1948, but no progress towards constructing the link was made.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] In the years after the Second World War, a series of preliminary plans for relieving congestion on the London Underground had considered various east–west routes through the Aldwych area, although other priorities meant that these were never proceeded with.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] An interchange was proposed at Aldwych and a second recommendation of the report was the revival of the link from Aldwych to Waterloo.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] London Transport had already sought legal powers from Parliament to construct tunnels from Aldwych to Waterloo in November 1964, and these were granted in the London Transport Act 1965 (c. xli) in August 1965.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] Detailed planning took place, although public spending cuts led to postponement of the scheme in 1967 before tenders were invited.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] Planning of the Fleet line continued and approval was given in the London Transport Act 1969 (c. l) in July 1969 for the first phase of the line, from Baker Street to Charing Cross.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] Tunnelling began on the £35 million route in February 1972 and the Jubilee line opened north from Charing Cross in May 1979.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] The tunnels of the approved section continued east of Charing Cross under Strand almost as far as Aldwych station, but no work at Aldwych was undertaken and they were used only as sidings.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] Funding for the second phase of the work was delayed throughout the 1970s whilst the route beyond Charing Cross was reviewed to consider options for serving anticipated development in the London Docklands area.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] By 1979, the cost was estimated as £325 million, a six-fold increase from the £51 million estimated in 1970.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] A further review of alternatives for the Jubilee line was carried out in 1980, which led to a change of priorities and the postponement of any further effort on the line.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] When the extension was eventually constructed in the late 1990s it took a different route, south of the River Thames via Westminster, Waterloo and London Bridge to provide a rapid link to Canary Wharf, leaving the tunnels between Green Park and Aldwych redundant.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] Following the station's closure, in 1996 the Civic Trust and other organisations including Transport 2000 proposed to create a heritage railway.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] The station would be restored to an inter-war appearance, and old Underground rolling stock would be used for journeys on the disused tracks.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] London Underground rejected the proposal on safety and cost grounds.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] In July 2005, Ove Arup & Partners produced a report, *DLR Horizon 2020 Study*, for the Docklands Light Railway (DLR) examining "pragmatic development schemes" to expand and improve the DLR network between 2012 and 2020.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] One of the proposals was an extension of the DLR from Bank to Charing Cross via City Thameslink and Aldwych.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] The disused Jubilee line tunnels would be enlarged to accommodate the larger DLR trains and Aldwych station would form the basis for a new station on the line, although requiring considerable reconstruction to accommodate escalators.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] The estimated cost in 2005 was £232 million for the infrastructure works and the scheme was described as "strongly beneficial" as it was expected to attract passengers from the London Underground's existing east–west routes and from local buses and reduce overcrowding at Bank station.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] The business case assessment was that the proposal offered high value, although similar values were calculated for other extension proposals from Bank.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] In 2015, a scheme was proposed by the design firm Gensler to convert disused London Underground tunnels into subterranean rail trails, enabling the disused branches of the Piccadilly line and Jubilee line to be used as cycle paths.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] The scheme, which would involve re-opening Aldwych station as an access point for cyclists, has not been officially approved.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] Because it was a self-contained section of the London Underground that was closed outside weekday peak hours, Aldwych station and the branch line from Holborn were popular locations for filming scenes set on the Tube even before their closure.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] Since the branch's closure in 1994, its use in film productions has continued, with the station appearing as itself and, with appropriate signage, as other stations on the network.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] The track and infrastructure are maintained in operational condition, and until 2021 a train of ex-Northern line 1972 tube stock was stabled on the branch.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] This train could be driven up and down the branch for filming.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] The physical connection with the Piccadilly line northbound tracks remains, but requires manual operation.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] The pre-war operation of the station features in a pivotal scene in Geoffrey Household's novel *Rogue Male*, when the pursuit of the protagonist by an enemy agent sees them repeatedly using the shuttle service on the branch line.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] A chase through Aldwych station ends with the agent's death by electrocution on the track.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] The station is the setting for the climax of the *Doctor Who* novel *The Pescatons*.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] A much modified and expanded version of the station appears as a level in the video game *Tomb Raider III*.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] The music video for The Prodigy's song "Firestarter" was filmed in the disused eastern tunnel and one of the unused lift shafts.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] The station was the subject of an episode of *Most Haunted* in 2002.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/aldwych-tube-station] The station was also the subject of an episode of The Magnus Archives in 2018.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/architectural-design-competition] An **architectural competition** is a type of design competition, in which an entity that intends to build new work, or is just seeking ideas, invites architects to submit design proposals.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/architectural-design-competition] The winning proposal is usually chosen by an independent panel of design professionals, stakeholders (such as government and local representatives, the leadership of a cultural institution, etc.) or public opinion.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/architectural-design-competition] The effect of architectural competitions varies with competition format.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/architectural-design-competition] Architectural competitions are often, though not exclusively, used to award commissions for public buildings: In some countries, government procurement rules for tendering public building contracts stipulate some form of open architectural competition.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/architectural-design-competition] Architectural competitions have existed for more than 2,500 years.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/architectural-design-competition] The design of the Acropolis, in Athens, resulted from an architectural competition in 448 B.C., as did several European cathedrals in the Middle Ages.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/architectural-design-competition] During the Renaissance, many projects initiated by the papacy or other top religious bodies were decided through design competition.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/architectural-design-competition] Examples are the Spanish Steps in Rome and, famously, the competition for the dome of the Florence Cathedral, won by Filippo Brunelleschi in 1419.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/architectural-design-competition] Open competitions emerged in the late 18th century in countries including the United States, Great Britain, Ireland, France, and Sweden.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/architectural-design-competition] In 19th century England and Ireland, more than 2,500 competitions were held within five decades, with 362 in London alone.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/architectural-design-competition] The Royal Institute of British Architects drafted its first set of rules in 1839 and its first formal regulations in 1872.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/architectural-design-competition] German regulations had been introduced in 1867.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/architectural-design-competition] In the same period, in the Netherlands, an association for the advancement of architecture (*Maatschappij tot Bevordering van de Bouwkunst*) started organizing conceptual competitions to stimulate creativity among architects.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/architectural-design-competition] The rules of each competition are defined by the organizer; they often, however, follow the guidelines provided by the International Union of Architects or the relevant national or regional architectural organization.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/architectural-design-competition] Competition guidelines define roles, responsibilities, processes, and procedures within a competition and provide guidance on possible competition types, eligibility criteria, jury composition, participation conditions, payments, prizes, publication of results, and other aspects.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/architectural-design-competition] In France and Germany, design competitions are compulsory for all public buildings exceeding a certain cost.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/architectural-design-competition] Winning first prize in a competition does not guarantee that the project will be realized.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/architectural-design-competition] The commissioning body often has the right to veto the winning design, and both requirements and finances may change, thwarting the original intention.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/architectural-design-competition] (Many competitions have been held and won before the financing was even in place.) The 2002 World Trade Center site design competition is an example of a highly publicized competition, in which only the basic elements of the winning design by Daniel Libeskind appeared in the finished project.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/architectural-design-competition] Most significant among architectural competitions are the ones which are internationally open, attract a large number of design submissions, and the winning design is built.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/associateship-of-king-s-college] The **Associateship of King's College** (**AKC**) award was the degree-equivalent qualification of King's College London from 1833.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/associateship-of-king-s-college] It is the original qualification that King's awarded to its students.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/associateship-of-king-s-college] In current practice, it is an optional award, unique to King's College London, that students can study in addition to their degree proper.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/associateship-of-king-s-college] After successfully completing the AKC course, participants may apply to be elected by the Academic Board of King's College London as an 'Associate of King's College' (AKC).
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/associateship-of-king-s-college] Once their election has been ratified, they are permitted to use the post-nominal letters "AKC" along with their main qualification.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/associateship-of-king-s-college] In December 1833 the college's council established a committee to organise the disparate courses offered at King's.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/associateship-of-king-s-college] As a result of this committee's report, the AKC was established by the college's council on 14 February 1834 as a three-year general course based on a core of divinity, mathematics, classics and English, with other options added in the second and third years.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/associateship-of-king-s-college] The first awards were made at the annual distribution of prizes in the General Department on 27 June 1835.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/associateship-of-king-s-college] From 1909, only students registered for a University of London degree at King's were normally allowed to study for the associateship.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/associateship-of-king-s-college] The two-year course involves weekly lectures concerning theology, ethics and philosophy.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/associateship-of-king-s-college] All members of staff at King's may study for the AKC as a free-standing qualification.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/associateship-of-king-s-college] From 2015, King's alumni—who in their student days opted out of the AKC study—can now study for the programme via distance learning.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/associateship-of-king-s-college] The 21st-century AKC offers a programme of inclusive, research-led lectures which allows students to explore diverse religious and cultural perspectives.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/associateship-of-king-s-college] The AKC is at the heart of the College's commitment to an international, interdisciplinary, and innovative curriculum: it seeks to foster an understanding of different beliefs and cultures that can be taken into wider society.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/associateship-of-king-s-college] The AKC programme is assessed by lecture attendance.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/associateship-of-king-s-college] Lecture attendance is demonstrated by a student's successful completion of a short, online, qualitative quiz after each lecture.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/associateship-of-king-s-college] Students must demonstrate attendance at 4/9 lectures during each series (semester) to gain a 'pass' mark.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/associateship-of-king-s-college] Gaining a 'pass' for all four series taken over the course of two years (subject to specific exceptions e.g. students studying abroad for part of their degree programme) entitles the students to wear an epitoge on their academic dress during their graduation exercises.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/associateship-of-king-s-college] After graduating from King's, students/alumni who succeed in the AKC exams are eligible to be elected as Associates of King's College by the Academic Board of King's College London.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/associateship-of-king-s-college] Staff who succeed in the AKC are likewise eligible for election.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/associateship-of-king-s-college] The AKC has been assessed via weekly qualitative quizzes since the academic year 2019/20.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/associateship-of-king-s-college] Up until the academic year 2019/20, students were assessed by an annual exam which included three equally weighted questions.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/associateship-of-king-s-college] Students were allowed to pick two questions from one semester, and one question from the other semester.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/associateship-of-king-s-college] Each question was based on a lecture that had taken place that academic year.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/associateship-of-king-s-college] Students who successfully completed the AKC achieved a 'pass' for the award overall.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/associateship-of-king-s-college] For each academic year, however, they will have achieved an assessment result that was given as a Pass (40-59), Pass with Merit (60-69) or Pass with Distinction (70+) depending on their average grade for the assessment that year.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/associateship-of-king-s-college] From 1848 to 1972, the Theological Department of King's College London (a distinct institution from King's College London and not to be confused with the latter's Faculty of Theology) awarded the *Theological AKC*.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/associateship-of-king-s-college] This was an ordination qualification in the Church of England and was a three-year, full-time course of studies.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/associateship-of-king-s-college] Some ordination candidates read the AKC only and some read the combined BD/AKC course, receiving both qualifications at the end of the three years.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/associateship-of-king-s-college] The Theological AKC was equivalent to a BA pass degree in theology.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/associateship-of-king-s-college] It was awarded in three classes with an undivided second class.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/associateship-of-king-s-college] Holders were entitled to wear distinctive academic dress by a grant of the Archbishop of Canterbury.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/associateship-of-king-s-college] The hood is of the "Cambridge shape" (MA), made of black poplin and edged, inside and out, with "one inch of mauve silk".
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/associateship-of-king-s-college] The gown resembles the classic MA design of the ancient universities with a few exceptions (*e.g.* it had a black button and cord at the back of the yoke).
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/associateship-of-king-s-college] Also, its sleeves are cut square, that is, without the "crescent" shaping of the other universities.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/baron-ferdinand-de-rothschild] Although Ferdinand de Rothschild was born in Paris in 1839, he was from Vienna and was a member of the Rothschild banking family of Austria.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/baron-ferdinand-de-rothschild] He was the second son of Anselm Salomon *Freiherr* von Rothschild (1803–1874), a Vienna-based banker, and his English wife Charlotte Nathan Rothschild (1807–1859), daughter of Nathan Mayer Rothschild.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/baron-ferdinand-de-rothschild] Ferdinand's great-grandfather was Mayer Amschel Rothschild.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/baron-ferdinand-de-rothschild] He had the hereditary title of *Freiherr* (baron) in the Austrian nobility.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/baron-ferdinand-de-rothschild] He was 'Ferdy' to his family and friends.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/baron-ferdinand-de-rothschild] When Ferdinand became a British subject and moved from Vienna to London, "[he] epitomised the expanding lifestyle of the fourth generation".
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/baron-ferdinand-de-rothschild] On 7 June 1865, he married his second cousin Evelina de Rothschild (1839–1866), the daughter of Baron Lionel de Rothschild (1808–1879).
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/baron-ferdinand-de-rothschild] On 4 December 1866, their son was stillborn, and Evelina died later the same day.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/baron-ferdinand-de-rothschild] In her memory, Ferdinand built, equipped and endowed the Evelina Hospital for Sick Children in Southwark, south London.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/baron-ferdinand-de-rothschild] From 1868 to 1875, he became Treasurer of the Jewish Board of Guardians and Warden of the Central Synagogue in 1870.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/baron-ferdinand-de-rothschild] During these roles, Ferdinand instigated an offer of £2,000 which ultimately led to the foundation of the Army Reservists' Home.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/baron-ferdinand-de-rothschild] In 1883, Ferdinand de Rothschild was High Sheriff of Buckinghamshire.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/baron-ferdinand-de-rothschild] He was adopted as a Liberal candidate for the London constituency of St George's in the East, but on being invited, he contested in 1885 another seat, at Aylesbury, which he won and held until his death.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/baron-ferdinand-de-rothschild] In 1886, over the issue of Irish Home Rule, he joined the Liberal Unionists and hosted meetings at Waddesdon Manor (where Joseph Chamberlain, Arthur Balfour and Lord Randolph Churchill were often guests) that led to the formation of the Unionist-Conservative alliance.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/baron-ferdinand-de-rothschild] From 1896, he was a Trustee of the British Museum, a role suggested by Sir Augustus Wollaston Franks and which led to his Renaissance collection being bequeathed to the British Museum after his death.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/baron-ferdinand-de-rothschild] This is now exhibited as the Waddesdon Bequest.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/baron-ferdinand-de-rothschild] Ferdinand de Rothschild died at Waddesdon Manor on his 59th birthday, thought to be the result of a cold caught when last visiting his wife's tomb.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/baron-ferdinand-de-rothschild] He was buried next to his wife at the Rothschild Mausoleum in the Jewish Cemetery at West Ham.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/baron-ferdinand-de-rothschild] Fluent in three languages, and considered "as much at home in Paris as in London", Ferdinand was an already inspired collector of eighteenth-century French decorative arts from his early twenties.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/baron-ferdinand-de-rothschild] For instance, when he was only 21 years old, his first purchase was made of one of the most ostentatious rococo Sèvres ship vases from the Louis XV era.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/baron-ferdinand-de-rothschild] His development into one of the most renowned collectors of the 19th century, even amongst the Rothschilds, is known by the abundance of family letters in which he is referred to as "curiosity-hunting... all over Europe".
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/baron-ferdinand-de-rothschild] In the autumn of 1874, Ferdinand de Rothschild bought land in the village of Waddesdon in Buckinghamshire from the Duke of Marlborough in order to build a property in which he could house his diverse collections.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/baron-ferdinand-de-rothschild] Between 1874 and 1889, architect Gabriel-Hippolyte Destailleur designed and built Waddesdon Manor, a 19th-century manor based on the 16th-century French Chateau de Chambord.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/baron-ferdinand-de-rothschild] He sought to 'revive the decoration of the eighteenth century in its purity, reconstructing the rooms out of old material, reproducing them as they had been during the reigns of Louis'.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/baron-ferdinand-de-rothschild] His collection of Renaissance *objets d'art* from the house was bequeathed to the British Museum, and under the terms of the bequest are still displayed there separately as the Waddesdon Bequest.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/baron-ferdinand-de-rothschild] The Holy Thorn Reliquary is a highlight of the collection, though its distinguished provenance was unknown until after World War II.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/baron-ferdinand-de-rothschild] He willed Waddesdon Manor to Alice Charlotte von Rothschild, his unmarried younger sister, who had lived with him there.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/baron-ferdinand-de-rothschild] Miss Alice, in turn, bequeathed the estate to their nephew, James Armand de Rothschild.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/baron-ferdinand-de-rothschild] Following James' death, the manor passed to the National Trust, in a special arrangement where the Rothschild family remain involved.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/evelina-london-children-s-hospital] The hospital was founded in 1869 (as Evelina Hospital for Sick Children) by Baron Ferdinand de Rothschild, whose wife, Evelina, and their child had died in premature labour.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/evelina-london-children-s-hospital] It was established in a purpose-built hospital in Southwark Bridge Road, Southwark, opposite what was originally the headquarters of the London Fire Brigade at 94 Southwark Bridge Road.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/evelina-london-children-s-hospital] It was brought under the management of Guy's Hospital in 1947 and became part of the National Health Service in 1948.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/evelina-london-children-s-hospital] In 1976 the original hospital building was closed, and the children's wards were moved to the newly built Guy's Tower.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/evelina-london-children-s-hospital] In 1999 a decision was made to re-establish Evelina Children's Hospital as a new specialist hospital for all children's services at Guy's and St Thomas', in Lambeth, on the site of a former nurses' home.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/evelina-london-children-s-hospital] An architectural design competition was managed by RIBA Competitions and won by Hopkins Architects and engineers Buro Happold.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/evelina-london-children-s-hospital] Davis Langdon provided quantity surveying and employer's agent services.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/evelina-london-children-s-hospital] Construction began in 2002, and the building was completed in 2004, ready for fitting out.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/evelina-london-children-s-hospital] The building won the IStructE Award for Education or Healthcare Structures in 2006.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/evelina-london-children-s-hospital] In the same year, after a Europe-wide heatwave, the building's project team were recalled following reports of high indoor temperatures.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/evelina-london-children-s-hospital] In 2018, it was announced that the Duchess of Cambridge would become the hospital's patron.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/evelina-london-children-s-hospital] The NHS Children's and Young People's Gender Service for London is the partnership between Evelina, Great Ormond Street Hospital and the South London and Maudsley NHS Foundation Trust to take over from the Tavistock and Portman NHS Foundation Trust in the South of England.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/evelina-london-children-s-hospital] In June 2020, aged five and inspired by Captain Tom Moore's NHS fundraising during the COVID-19 pandemic, Tony Hudgell set out to raise £500 for Evelina London Children's Hospital by walking 10km on his prosthetic legs.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/evelina-london-children-s-hospital] The figure quickly topped £1 million, with the final amount raised totalling £1.7 million.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/evelina-london-children-s-hospital] South Thames Retrieval Service (STRS) is a children's acute transport service which specialises in the inter-hospital transfer of critically ill children in London south of the River Thames.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/evelina-london-children-s-hospital] It operates from the children's intensive care unit of the Evelina London Children's Hospital.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/evelina-london-children-s-hospital] The unit is the lead centre for children's intensive care in the South Thames region and manages the clinical network for children's (paediatric) intensive care via the retrieval service, in conjunction with the intensive care units at St George's Hospital and King's College Hospital.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/evelina-london-children-s-hospital] With one phone call to the emergency number, a clinician in a South Thames hospital, can source clinical advice, a PICU bed and a transport team as necessary.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/evelina-london-children-s-hospital] STRS can then also coordinate specialist service input (e.g. cardiology).
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/evelina-london-children-s-hospital] Alice Cross trained as a nurse at St Bartholomew's Hospital and was appointed Lady Superintendent at the Evelina in 1879, a post she held for 24 years.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/evelina-london-children-s-hospital] During her time as Lady Superintendent she recognised the importance of the provision of convalescence for children having undergone surgery at the hospital and petitioned for the refurbishment of the convalescent home in Banstead Surrey for children.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/evelina-london-children-s-hospital] She is acknowledged on the plaque commemorating the founding of the hospital 1869.
[src:evelina-london-children-s-hospital/evelina-london-children-s-hospital] Baron Ferdinand de Rothschild left a legacy of £500.00 to her in his will.
